UPON INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER, ONE (1) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM WAS DISCOVERED DAMAGED. APPARENTLY THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED IN TRANSIT WHICH CAUSED THE DRUM TO BECOME DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF RESIN SOLUTION WERE RELEASED. THE MAJORITY OF RESIN SOLUTION WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE TRAILER AND APPROXIMATELY ONE (1) PINT RELEASED TO THE ASPHALT SURFACE BENEATH THE TRAILER. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES OFFLOADED THE TRAILER AND CLEANED THE CONTAMINATED DRUMS. ABSORBENT CLAY AND ABSORBENT PADS WERE APPLIED TO THE FREE LIQUID INSIDE THE TRAILER. SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES ALSO APPLIED KITTY LITTER TO THE AFFECTED ASPHALT SURFACE. CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE (1) FIFTY-FIVE GALLON DRUM. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO ONE (1) EIGHTY-FIVE GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM. DISPOSAL WILL BE COORDINATED PER LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THIS HAD EFFECT OF CAUSING TWO OF THE 20 GLASS BOTTLES IN THE PACKAGE TO BREAK, RELEASING THEIR CONTENTS. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE PACKAGE WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 69 SOUTH AT THE INTERSECTION OF US HIGHWAY 224 IN MARKLE, INDIANA, THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. DRIVER ENCOUNTERED AN ACCIDENT BETWEEN TWO TRACTOR-TRAILER UNITS.  THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO AVOID THIS ACCIDENT.  AS A RESULT, DAMAGE TO THE TRACTOR AND BOTH TRAILERS OF THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. UNIT OCCURRED.  THE HUNTINGTON COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE.  HAZMAT ONE OF LOATHE, KANSAS WAS CONTACTED TO COORDINATE THE CLEANUP.  HAZMAT ONE DISPATCHED ERS, INC. OF FORT WAYNE, INDIANA TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  UPON INVESTIGATION, FOURTEEN DAMAGED FIVE GALLON STEEL PAILS OF A REGULATED ADHESIVES AND A NON-REGULATED COMPOUNDS ADHESIVE, N.O.I. LIQUID PRODUCT WERE DISCOVERED.  APPROXIMATELY FIFTEEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND AFFECTED THE TRAILER, THE ROAD SURFACE, AND THE ROAD SHOULDER. ERS, INC. WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THE CLEANUP ACTIVITIES.  NO HAZMAT-RELATED INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDSS WERE REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE WET CARTON CONTAINING ONE LEAKING, ONE GALLON METAL CAN WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 1 CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  THE DAMAGE TO THE CAN WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT, WHICH CAUSED A PALLET TO FALL AND HIT THE CARTON.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENT TOWELS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, WET CARTON AND ONE DAMAGED CAN WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON STEEL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING AT THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. FACILITY, A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE FREIGHT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM HAD RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 2 OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT. APPARENTLY PRESSURE INSIDE THE DRUM CAUSED THE DRUM TO BEGIN TO BREAK AT THE SEAMS WHICH CAUSED THE RELEASE.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL USED LEVEL D PPE TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  ABSORBENT RAGS WERE USED TO ABSORB THE FREE LIQUID ON THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE (1) 30-GALLON FIBER ALONG WITH THE PPE TO BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING INSPECTION AND SHIPPER ARRIVAL.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING AT THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. FACILITY, ONE (1) 50-GALLON METAL DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT.  APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS WERE RELEASED INSIDE THE TRAILER, AND A MINIMAL AMOUNT ALSO RELEASED TO THE GROUND BENEATH THE TRAILER.  TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C EQUIPMENT.  THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO A 50-GALLON RECOUP DRUM.  ABSORBENT PADS WERE APPLIED TO THE FREE PRODUCT INSIDE THE TRAILER AND ON THE GROUND.  CLEANUP MATERIALS, ABSORBENT PADS, PPE, AND CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD WERE PLACED INTO TWO (2) 50-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE (1) 10-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH THE PPE TO BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSITION.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, FOUR LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED ON THE DOCK. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE LEAKING BUNGS ON THE FOUR, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY DRUMS WERE TIGHTENED, AND THE FOUR DRUMS WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE LOADING, TWO, DAMAGED FIVE GALLON PLASTIC PAILS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE FIRST QUARTER OF THE TRAILER.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE PAIL WAS LEAKING AND ONE WAS DAMAGED.  APPROXIMATELY, THREE GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY A FORKLIFT.   TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES AND ABSORBENTS.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND LEAKING PAIL WERE PLACED INTO ONE TEN GALLON METAL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DAMAGED PAIL WAS PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM.  BOTH RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE UNLOADING, ONE FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING FOUR, TWO LITER PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT ONE PLASTIC BOTTLE WAS LEAKING AND THE REMAINING THREE BOTTLES WERE UNAFFECTED.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE FIBERBOARD BOX BEING PUNCTURED BY AN UNKNOWN CAUSE DURING TRANSIT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG.  THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, FIBERBOARD BOX AND LEAKING TWO LITER PLASTIC BOTTLE WERE PLACED INTO TWO, THIRTY-THREE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS AND INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  ALL THREE DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION.  THE THREE UNAFFECTED TWO LITER PLASTIC BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER OVERPACK DRUM, WHICH WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF ANY LEAKAGE FROM THE MANWAY COVER. ALL OF THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE MADE WRENCH TIGHT AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

column168: ON 10-07-2003, CXS TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT WAS ADVISED THAT THE METRO TRANSIT AUTHORITY HAD RESPONDED TO A LEAKING TANK CAR THE PREVIOUS NIGHT.  THE INITIAL REPORT INDICATED THE LEAKING CAR WAS IN CSXT'S RAIL YARD.  THE LOCAL TRAINMASTER INVESTIGATED THE REPORT AND DETERMINED THE LEAKING TANK CAR, PLEX 3362, LOAD LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS, HAD BEEN DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING VAPORS ON THE CUSTOMER'S SIDING AT BURNWELL GAS.  A REPRESENTATIVE OF BURNWELL GAS EXPLAINED THAT PLEX 3362 WAS BEING UNLOADED ON 10-06.  THEY WERE NOT ABLE TO COMPLETE UNLOADING THE CAR SO THEY DISCONNECTED IT FROM THE UNLOADING RACK, LEAVING THE UNLOADING PIPE EXTENSIONS CONNECTED AND MOVED THE CAR.  ABOUT MIDNIGHT, THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE METRO NORTH COMMUTER RAILROAD REPORTING STRONG L P GAS ODOR IN THE AREA.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED, FOUND THE CAR AND NOTIFIED BURNWELL GAS.  BURNWELL GAS PERSONNEL RESPONDED. THEY ENSURED THE VALVES WERE CLOSED, THEN REMOVED THE UNLOADING PIPE EXTENSIONS AND INSTALLED THE VALVE PLUGS AND THE VAPOR LEAK STOPPED.  ON 10-07, THE REMAINDER OF THE PRODUCT IN THE CAR WAS UNLOADED.  BURNWELL GAS INDICATED THEY OBSERVED NO PROBLEMS WITH THE VALVES OR PLUGS.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED LATER ON 10-07.

column168: GATX 300835, LOAD GASOLINE, WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET IN CSX TRANSPORTATION'S WYOMING YARD, IN GRAND RAPIDS, MI.  THE TRAINMASTER REPORTED THE LEAK AS A CONTINUOUS STREAM SMALLER THAN A PENCIL IN SIZE. CSXT PERSONNEL PLACED A TRASHCAN UNDER THE LEAK TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT. THE SHIPPER, QUADRA ENERGY, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM AROUND THE THREADS ON THE BOTTOM OUTLET EXTENSION BELL CAP.  THEY FOUND THAT THE TOP-OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN SLIGHTLY.  THEY ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE VALVE BUT PRODUCT CONTINUED TO LEAK.  AFTER 2 TO 3 ATTEMPTS, THE CONTRACTOR EMPLOYED A PIPE WRENCH TO TIGHTENED UP THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  THE CONTRACTOR REMOVED THE BELL CAP TO DRAIN THE EXTENSION PIPE AND TO VERIFY THAT THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED.  THE CAP WAS INSTALLED AND MADE WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CONTRACTOR SOLIDIFIED 3 GALLONS OF PRODUCT CONTAINED IN THE TRASH CAN AND WILL PROCESS IT FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER WAS ADVISED OF THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, FREE PRODUCT WAS DISCOVERED ON THE TOP OF ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON POLY DRUM AT THE HALFWAY MARK OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE BUNG. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LOOSE BUNG WAS TIGHTENED AND THE DRUM WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE AT THE TERMINAL ONE, FORTY-FOUR POUND PAPER BAG WAS DAMAGED DURING LOADING. APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. THE DAMAGE TO THE BAG WAS DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION, ABSORBENTS, A LARGE BROOM, A SHOVEL, A WISK BROOM AND A DUST PAN. THE DAMAGED BAG WAS PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE PERSONAL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO ANOTHER THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE SHOVEL AND BROOMS WENT INTO A FIFTEEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE FREE PRODUCT AND ABSORBENTS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. ALL FOUR RECOVERY DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. ONE EXPOSURE WAS REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THE SPILL. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS REQUIRED. THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, SIX DAMAGED FIFTY POUND PLASTIC BAGS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY, TENTY POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING, CAUSING A PALLET TO TEAR THE BAGS. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTIONS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE SIX DAMAGED BAGS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. ALL FEDERAL, STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED. JIM CAMPBELL AND SHELLY WISE OF ROADWAY EXPRESS,INC. WERE CONTACTED TO DISCUSS REPORTING.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, AN ODOR WAS DETECTED COMING FROM THE TRAILER. THE TRAILER WAS ISOLATED. AIRGAS SPECIALTY GASES, THE SHIPPER SENT A HAZMAT TEAM TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP. UPON INVESTIGATION BY AIRGAS, ONE LEAKING, ONE HUNDRED AND THIRTY-ONE POUND STEEL CYLINDER WAS DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY, TWENTY-FIVE POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A LOOSE RELEASE VALVE. AIRGAS REPAIRED THE RELEASE VALVE AND THE LEAKING CYLINDER WILL BE FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column168: A FIBERBOARD BOX WAS BEING RELOADED IN ATLANTA WHEN THEY NOTICED A DARK STAIN ON THE BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE AND THE FIBERBOARD WAS RIPPED. UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE THEY FOUND SEVERAL ITEMS TO INCLUDE UNDECLARED AEROSOL CANS OF SPRAY PAINT. ONE OF THE CANS HAD LEAKED FROM A SEAM, IT MIGHT HAVE BEEN DROPPED DURING SHIPMENT BUT NO ONE KNOWS WHEN OR WHERE. NO REAL CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED SINCE THE PAINT WAS DRY AND CONFINED TO THE PACKAGE. THE PACKAGE IS BEING HELD AT THE FEDEX ATLANTA RAMP PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. A MESSAGE WAS LEFT ON THE SHIPPER'S ANSWERING MACHINE BUT THEY DID NOT RETURN THE CALL.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS TRAVELING EAST ON HIGHWAY 286 GOING UP A SLIGHT GRADE AND APPROACHING A SHALLOW RIGHT TURN. HIGHWAY 286 IS A NARROW TWO LANE STATE HIGHWAY WITH NO SHOULDER ON EITHER SIDE. AS THE DRIVER WAS GOING THROUGH THE SHALLOW TURN HE, NOTICED TWO VEHICLES APPROACHING IN THE OPPOSITE DIRECTION THAT WERE RIGHT ON THE DOUBLE YELLOW CENTER LINES. HE TRIED TO MOVE OVER AND GIVE THESE VEHICLES AS MUCH ROOM AS POSSIBLE. HE MOVED TO THE RIGHT TOO FAR AND THE RIGHT TRAILER WHEELS SLIPPED OF THE PAVEMENT INTO A SMALL DITCH LINE. THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO STEER THE TRAILER BACK ONTO THE PAVEMENT BEFORE LOOSING CONTROL OF THE TRACTOR. THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER ENDED UP ROLLING ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE AND CAME TO A STOP IN THE RIGHT LANE OF THE HIGHWAY. SPILLED PRODUCT CAME FROM THE TOP REAR CLEAN OUT CAP ON THE CARGO TANK. AS THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER, THIS PORTION OF THE TRAILER STRUCK A TREE CAUSING THE CLEAN OUT CAP ATTACHMENT POINT TO BE PUSHED REARWARD. THIS RIPPED A SMALL HOLE IN THE BARREL ADJACENT TO THE CLEAN OUT CAP. ALL SPILLED PRODUCT WAS REMOVED FROM THE SCENE TO THE SATISFACTION OF LOCAL AND STATE OFFICIALS THAT ATTENDED THE SCENE

THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED TO COLLECT THE UNDAMAGED PORTION OF THE SHIPMENT.  WASTE FROM THE CLEANUP ACTIVITY WAS STAGED FOR DISPOSAL WITH A LOCAL CONTRACTOR.

SUNDAY 10/5/03 DRIVER HAD STOPPED TO TAKE A 8HR BREAK.  DRIVER STATED THAT HE HAD WALK AROUND THE UNIT CHECKING THE TIRES, LIGHTS, AND LOAD.  THE DRIVER THEN WENT TO BED.  ABOUT 4:00 PM DRIVER WAS CALLED TO TELL HIM THAT HIS TRAILER WAS LEAKING PRODUCT.  DRIVER THEN CALLED SAFETY TO REPORT THE LEAK.  THE SAFETY DEPT. THEN CALLED MARSHALL MILLER ENVIRONMENTAL TO TAKE CARE OF PROBLEM.  TIMOTHY WHITLOCK WAS THE PERSON IN CHARGE OF CLEAN UP. THE PROBLEM WAS WHEN THE LIFT TRUCK LOADED THE DRS THAT IT PUT TO MUCH PRESSURE ON THE DRUMS CAUSING THE DRS TO LEAK.  WASTE RECOVERY SOLUTIONS STATED TO ME THAT THIS PROBLEM WOULD NOT HAPPEN AGAIN BECAUSE THEY ARE GOING TO CHANGE THE WAY OF LOADING DRS.

THE DRIVER WAS STOPPED BY THE IOWA HIGHWAY PATROL ON US INTERSTATE 380 DUE TO MATERIAL LEAKING FROM THE CARGO TANKER.  THE WATERLOO EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM (WATERLOO FIRE DEPARTMENT) WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE AND PROCEEDED TO INVESTIGATE THE SPILL.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL (APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT) WAS FOUND ON THE TOP RAIL OF THE CARGO TANK, AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR DOME LID SEAL.  THE REAR DOME LID WAS NOT COMPLETELY SECURED AND A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL SEEPED OUT OF THE DOME LID WHILE IN TRANSIT.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM NEUTRALIZED THE MATERIAL.  THE SMALL AMOUNT OF NEUTRALIZED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED FROM THE TANKER WITH ABSORBENT PADS.  A FULL DOT INSPECTION WAS PERFORMED BY THE IOWA HIGHWAY PATROL, AND THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED TO COMPLETE THE DELIVERY. THE DRIVER WAS RETRAINED ON PROPER PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCEDURES AND HOW TO PROPERLY SECURE ALL TANKER OPENINGS PRIOR TO TRANSPORTING A LOAD.

DOCKMEN WAS PUTTING 55 GAL DRUM ON PALLET WHEN A BOARD BROKE ON THE PALLET CAUSING DRIVER TO FALL INTO THE MOST OF THE FORKLIFT. A SMALL PUNCTURE ABOUT 4" FROM THE TOP OF DRUM WAS RESULT OF THE FALL. A PAPER TOWEL WAS USED TO WIPE RELEASED MATERIAL OFF THE DRUM AND "FAST STEEL" WAS PLACED OVER THE PUNCTURE. I CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND ASHLAND TO REPORTED INCIDENT. THE REPAIRED DRUM WAS MONITORED FOR 2.5 HRS. TO INSURE THERE WAS NO LEAK. ASHLAND CHEMICAL RELEASED TO DELIVER TO CUSTOMER UPON THEIR REQUEST. THE DOCKMAN WAS ISSUED A "FOCUS QUALITY ERROR AVOIDANCE" TO INSURE THE ASSOCIATE HAD RECEIVED TRAINING ON PAPER TECHNIQUES MOVING DRUMS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THE ERROR WAS CAUSED BY NOT USING PROPER TOOLS WHEN HANDLING DRUMS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.

WE CONTACTED SHIPPER TO INVESTIGATE HOW BAG WAS PUNCTURED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAGE OF THE SHIPPER'S (ASHLAND) FORKLIFT DAMAGED/PUNCTURED BAG AT TIME OF LOAD.

IMPROPER BRACING/BLOCKING.  DRUMS SLID TOGETHER AS DRIVER BRAKED NEAR SERVICE STATION.  SPILL DISCOVERED.  SPILL CONTAINED WITH DAY SWEEP & PAPER TOWEL.  AUDIT SENT TO ORIGIN FOR PROPER FOLLOW-UP.  DRIVER RESECURED WITH EPOXY -PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM TO DESTINATION.

WHEN WE OPENED THE DOOR OF THE TRAILER & WE NOTICED A STRONG SMELL.  WE GOT THE PAPER WORK, FOUND OUT WHAT IT WAS AND LOCATED THE FREIGHT,  AFTER GETTING THE FREIGHT ONTO THE DOCK, WE CUT THE SHIPPER'S ORIGINAL SHRINK WRAP TO LOCATED THE LEAKING CONTAINER.  IN THE MIDDLE OF THE PALLET THERE WAS 5 CANS SEVERELY DENTED AND ONE RIGHT IN THE MIDDLE THAT HAD EPOXY ON THE SIDE OF IT AND WAS VERY LIGHT.  THIS WAS THE LEAKER.  WE PULLED THIS OFF OF THE SHIPMENT, PUT IT IN OUR OSD AREA AND SENT THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT ON.  CONTACTED SHIPPER AND INFORMED THEM OF THE UNSEEN DAMAGE THAT MAY BE CAUSED AT ORIGIN WAREHOUSE AND IMPROPER RESEALING OF THE CONTAINER.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOURS, 10-17-30, AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID OCCURRED AT THE APRIA HEALTHCARE FACILITY AT 2850 E. VALENCIA DRIVE, TUCSON, AZ. THE RELEASE WAS THE RESULT OF A FAILURE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE DURING A MAINTENANCE PROCEDURE ON THE APRIA HEALTHCARE 6000 GALLON OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID (CRYOGENIC OXYGEN) STAND TANK. LAMAR GEORGE, A TECHNICIAN FROM CACTUS MEDICAL, HAD JUST REMOVED A PRESSURE REGULATOR FOR MAINTENANCE WHEN THE PRESSURE BUILDING VALVE SEPARATED FROM THE TANK. JEFF FUENNING, TRANSPORTATION LEAD, AT THE APRIA FACILITY CONTACTED THE TUCSON FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAD THE AREA SURROUNDING THE TANK SECURED FROM VEHICLE AND PEDESTRIAN TRAFFIC. AS A SAFETY PRECAUTION THE FACILITY WAS EVACUATED, WITH APPROXIMATELY 35 EMPLOYEES BEING INVOLVED IN THE EVACUATION. THE RELEASE CONTINUED FOR APPROXIMATELY 25 MINUTES UNTIL THE TANK WAS EMPTY. THE RELEASE RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 1374 GALLONS OF OXYGEN, REFRIGERATED LIQUID WHICH EVAPORATED. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR COLLATERAL DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1156 HOURS THE TUCSON FIRE DEPARTMENT DECLARED THE SCENE SECURED AND THE PERSONNEL REENTERED THE BUILDING. TECHNICIANS FROM AIR PRODUCTS ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 HRS. AND INITIATED REPAIRS TO THE TANK THE REPAIRS WERE COMPLETED AND THE TANK WAS RETURNED TO SERVICE ON 10-20-03.

column168: DRIVER PULLED INTO BULK PLANT TO UNLOAD 7500 GALS CLEAR #1 FUEL OIL. GOT HOOKED UP TO PROPER TANK BUT DID NOT CHECK GAUGE ON THE TANK TO SEE IF LOAD WOULD FIT. STARTED PUMPING OF COMPT. OF 3500 GALS FOR WHICH ONLY 2500 WOULD FIT. DRIVER WAS DOING PAPERWORK WHICH IS AGAINST COMPANY POLICY. AND 1000 GALS OF CLEAR #1 FUEL OIL RAN OUT OF THE TANK VENT AND INTO THE DIKE CONTAINMENT. PRODUCT WAS PULLED OUT OF DIKE CONTAINMENT AND PUT IN A EMPTY TANK. ROCK THAT WAS IN THE DIKE WAS REMOVED AND HAULED TO LANDFILL. THE LINER IN THE CONTAINMENT WORKED WELL AND WE WERE ABLE TO RETAIN ALL PROD.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER LOADED UNIT AT SUNOCO'S MALVERN PA TERMINAL AT 16:27 ON 10/14/03 AND PROCEEDED TO DELIVERY LOCATION THAT WAS APPROXIMATELY 1-1/2 MILES AWAY.  ON THE DELIVERY ROUTE THE DRIVER WAS REQUIRED TO TURN LEFT FROM MOREHALL ROAD TO ROUTE 29 SOUTH.  THE ROADWAY AT THIS INTERSECTION HAS A SLOPE OF -3.1% AND A SUPER-ELEVATION OF -4.5%.  AS DRIVER MANEUVERED INTO THE 90% LEFT TURN AT A SPEED OF 20 MPH THE TRAILER OVERTURNED AND THE UNIT CAME TO REST ON IT'S RIGHT SIDE ON THE SIDE OF THE ROADWAY FACING TOWARDS ROUTE 29 SOUTH.  AS TRAILER CONTACTED ROADWAY THE TANK SHELL WAS CRACKED AT A WELD SEAM ON THE TOP RIGHT REAR BULKHEAD WHICH RESULTED IN THE PRODUCT LEAK, WHEN TRAILER CONTACTED ROADWAY ALL INTERNAL BULKHEADS WERE DAMAGED CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK  THROUGH EACH BULKHEAD AND OUT CRACK IN TANK SHELL.  WHEN INCIDENT OCCURRED POLICE AND EMERGENCY DEPARTMENTS WERE NOTIFIED AND SPILL CONTRACTORS AND SUNOCO PERSONNEL WERE DISPATCHED TO SCENE.  NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (INCIDENT# 702521) WAS NOTIFIED.  PREVENTION: ROUTING TO THIS DELIVERY LOCATION WAS CHANGED TO AVOID THIS TURN AT THIS INTERSECTION. ALL DRIVERS (AT ALL LOCATIONS) RECEIVED STAND DOWN TRAINING CONCERNING TRUCK ROLLOVERS DURING THE WEEK OF 11/3/03.

THIS RAILCAR WAS OBSERVED VENTING DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED.  UPON CLOSER INSPECTION, THE BOLTS ON THE LIQUID FLANGE WERE FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  THE BOLTS WERE  TIGHTENED,  AND THE INCIDENT WAS SECURED.

THIS RAILCAR WAS OBSERVED VENTING DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED.  UPON CLOSER INSPECTIONS, THE LIQUID VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE OPEN AND VALVE PLUG WAS FOUND TO BE LOOSE.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE PLUG WAS TIGHTENED.  THE INCIDENT WAS SECURED AT 0100 HOURS.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING TRL 264762 FROM DTR, IT WAS REPORTED TO ME FROM JACK MUHAW THAT A SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING ON HIS TRL. AFTER CHECKING THE MANIFEST, IT WAS FOUND TO BE PRO #596469005. 3 DRUMS ON THIS PRO WERE LEAKING. HEAVY FRT WAS STACKED ON TOP OF THIS WITH IMPROPER DUNNAGE CAUSING 3 OF THE 8 DRUMS TO LOOSE SOME OF THEIR CONTENTS. INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO EMER RESPONSE #18002553924 AS DIRECTED ON BILL REPORT # IS 1586.
OTHER FREIGHT PLACED ON TOP OF HAZMAT PUNCTURING 1 CARTON CAUSING SPILLAGE. THERE WERE NO INJURIES.

TCDX 11129 WAS NOTED BY CARRIER PERSONNEL WITH PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR AS IT WAS BEING SPOTTED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S PLANT. THE FACILITY RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. INVESTIGATION REVEALED 4 LOOSE BOTTOM OUTLET FLANGE BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT. THE BOLTS WERE PROPERLY TIGHTENED STOPPING THE RELEASE. GAUGING OF THE CONTENTS REVEALED A LOSS OF 2 INCHES OF PRODUCT WHICH EQUALS 2,678 POUND OR 176 GALLONS +/-.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, ONE CARDBOARD CARTON CONTAINING A ONE GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, CARDBOARD CARTON AND LEAKING ONE GALLON PLASTIC PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC DRUM WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TEN GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TERMINAL YARD. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PACKAGING FAILURE; THE DRUM WAS OVERFILLED AND LEAKED THROUGH THE PACKAGING MATERIAL. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO THREE, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS AND TWO, THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS, ALL OF WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO ONE, SIXTY-FIVE GALLON PLASTIC OVERPACK DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING SHIPPER INSTRUCTIONS. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, ONE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED AT THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ONE CUP OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE DRUM BEING PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENTS. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE LEAKING FIFTY-FIVE GALLON METAL DRUM WAS PATCHED WITH NU-DOUGH AND PLACED INTO A NINETY GALLON METAL OVERPACK DRUM. BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE DAMAGED CARDBOARD BOX CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON PLASTIC JUGS WAS DISCOVERED ON A WOODEN PALLET. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT TWO JUGS WERE DAMAGED AND THE REMAINING TWO JUGS WERE AFFECTED. APPROXIMATELY TWO GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE DOCK. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT. THE BOXES SHIFTED ON THE PALLET, CAUSING ONE BOX TO BREAK ON THE CORNER OF THE PALLET. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, GOGGLES, AMPHOMAG, A DUSTPAN AND WHISKBROOM. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS, DAMAGED BOX, AND TWO DAMAGED JUGS WERE PLACED INTO ONE, TEN GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM, WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION. THE TWO AFFECTED JUGS WERE CLEANED, REPACKAGED AND WERE FORWARDED ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED .

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION, THREE LEAKING THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER DRUMS WERE DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY TWELVE HUNDRED POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE DRUMS BEING CRUSHED BY THE WALL OF THE TRAILER DURING LOADING. THE THREE LEAKING THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER DRUMS WERE RETURNED TO THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. TERMINAL IN LAREDO, TEXAS. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO TWO, THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUMS. THE THREE LEAKING THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER DRUMS WERE PLACED INTO THREE, THIRTY-FIVE GALLON FIBER OVERACK DRUMS. ALL FIVE DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. ALL FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

AT 4:00 PM., OCTOBER 25, 2003, ENERGIS PERSONNEL WERE PREPARING TO UNLOAD A RAILCAR (GATX 33490) WHEN APPROXIMATELY 1234 GALLONS OF THICK SLUDGE TEXTURED FUEL WERE RELEASED FROM THE RAILCAR.  ENERGIS INITIALLY REPORTED A POSSIBLE RELEASE OF UP TO 4000 GALLONS.  RAILCAR MEASUREMENTS CONFIRMED A RELEASE OF 1234 GALLONS.  ENERGIS PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY EMPLOYED THE EMERGENCY SPILL VALVE KIT TO STOP THE FLOW AND FOAMED THE AFFECTED AREA. THE FOAM APPLICATION TO REDUCE VAPORS WAS COMPLETED AND THE DOORS CLOSED TO THE UNLOADING AREA BY 4:05 P.M... ALL SPILLAGE OCCURRED WITHIN CONCRETE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT.  THE SPILLED FUEL WAS RECOVERED INTO THE PROPER TANK.  ALL ABSORBENT PADS, PPE, ETC., USED FOR CLEANUP WERE PLACED IN DRUMS AND WILL BE SHIPPED OFF FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE WASTE CODES ASSOCIATED WITH THE MATERIAL ARE ALSO ATTACHED.  THE ENTIRE RELEASE COVERED AN AREA OF 969 SQUARE FEET.  A SAMPLE OF THE SPILLED SLUDGE WAS TAKEN TO THE LABORATORY TO DETERMINE THE EVAPORATION RATE.  EMISSION CALCULATIONS OF THE RELEASED VAPORS ARE ATTACHED.  THE TOTAL RELEASE OF 9.17 LBS. TO ATMOSPHERE DID NOT RELEASE IN A REPORTABLE QUANTITY.  OTHER PERTINENT FACTS: --THERE WAS NO RELEASE TO THE SOIL OR WATER. --THE WASTE DERIVED FUEL CONTAINED NO EXTREMELY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES.  --NO INJURIES OCCURRED.  --PROPER UNLOADING AND EMERGENCY PROCEDURES WERE USED BY ENERGIS EMPLOYEES.  THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE SPILL WAS A FAULTY RAILCAR VALVE.  --ALL PROPER AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED BY 4:51.. --NO EVACUATION WAS REQUIRED.  --NO ACTUAL OR POTENTIAL HAZARDS TO HUMAN HEALTH OR THE ENVIRONMENT REMAIN AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.

ON OCTOBER 13, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 0005 HOURS, MEMBERS OF A KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) YARD CREW REPORTED VENTING FROM THE VALVE CABINET ON THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR NO BTAX 1017 LOADED WITH ARGON REFRIGERATED LIQUID, 2.2//UN1951 AT THE KANSAS CITY, MISSOURI KCS RAILROAD YARD. AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE AND TIGHTENED A VALVE AT 0155 HOURS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO ITS DESTINATION. * LEAKING FROM VALVE CABINET.
WHILE UNLOADING AT OUR LITTLE ROCK TERMINAL THEY NOTICED A BOX LEAKING CAUSED BY FORKLIFT BLADES. THE PRODUCT WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY CONTAINER AND IS BEING HELD FOR DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING SHIPMENT CAME IN CONTACT WITH A TRUCK SPRING TEARING A HOLE IN THE CARTON CAUSING CONTENTS TO SPILL IN TRAILER. USED KITTY LITTER ABSORBENT TO CONTAIN AND CLEANED SPILL FROM TRAILER, DOCKWORKER WAS ADVISED TO TAKE EXTRA PRECAUTION WHEN UNLOADING HM'S BE GETTING OFF THE FORKLIFT AND BE AWARE OF HIS SURROUNDINGS.

ON OCTOBER 28TH, LANGER TRANSPORT DELIVERED A LOAD OF 2-ETHYL HEXYL ACRYLATE TO ASHLAND CHEMICAL IN TOTOWA, NEW JERSEY. WE HAD TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER USING A PUMP THAT IS LOCATED ON OUR TRACTOR. AS WE STARTED TO UNLOAD THE TRAILER, THE DRIVER EXPERIENCED A MINOR PROBLEM, WHICH LEAD TO A SPILL OF LOESS THAN 20 GALLON OF A PRODUCT CALLED 2-ETHYL HEXYL ACRYLATE. THE PROBLEM AROSE BECAUSE THE DRIVER FAILED TO VENT OFF THE TRAILER. WITHOUT THE TRAILER BEING VENTED IT BUILT A VACUUM AND PARTIALLY IMPLODED. A SMALL CRACK APPEARED IN THE SHELL OF THE TRAILER. THIS CRACK LED TO PRODUCT BEING RELEASED OUT OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE GROUND. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITH PADS AND THE SECTION WAS ROPED OFF SO THAT NO ONE COULD GET CLOSE TO THE PRODUCT. WE WERE NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AS SOON AS THE SPILL OCCURRED. WE RUSHED TO THE SCENE TO EVALUATE THE SITUATION AND CALLED OPTECH TO CLEANUP THE SPILL. ALL EMPLOYEES OF LANGER TRANSPORT HAVE BEEN SPOKEN TO ABOUT THIS INCIDENT. WE HAVE RE-TRAINED AND INSTRUCTED ALL DRIVERS ON THE CORRECT PROCESS FOR UNLOADING. PICTURES OF THE SPILL WERE SHOWN TO ALL OF OUR DRIVERS IN ORDER FOR THEM TO UNDERSTAND THE SEVERITY OF THIS INCIDENT.
NO DUNNAGE ON PALLET SO NAIL RUBBED PINHOLE LEAK IN CONTAINER.
AT TIME OF UNLOADING A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS NOTICED AROUND LID AREA AND DOWN THE LABEL.  CUSTOMER REFUSED CONTAINER WHICH WAS THEN PLACED IN A CARDBOARD BOX & SECURED TO THE TRAILER WALL.
FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS MOVING A PALLET NEXT TO SPILLED MATERIAL.  HE FORCED THE BACK PALLET INTO THE PALLET THAT SPILLED PUTTING A HOLE IN THE DRUM.

DOCKMAN MOVED SKID OFF THE DOCK TO LOAD ON DELIVERING TRAILER WHEN HE NOTICED A WET SPOT ON DOCK.  DOCK MAN LIFTED SKID UP AND NOTICED ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS DRIPPING AROUND A PATCH AT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED AND ERTS RESPONDED TO DIRECT CLEANUP OF THE SPILLAGE.

UPON COUPLING TO RAILCAR EDCX 6039, THE TOWER RETARDER OPERATOR NOTED "WHITE SMOKE" EMANATING FROM THE AREA. FURTHER INSPECTION BY SOUTH JERSEY DIVISION ASSISTANT SUPERINTENDENT L. SARANDREA NOTED THE MANWAY COVER OF TANK CAR TCDX 11010 HAD APPARENTLY COME OFF DURING THE COUPLING, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE, ONTO THE GROUND AND SURROUNDING RAIL CARS. FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE 8-BOLT MANWAY COVER, FOUND APPROXIMATELY 35-40' FEET FROM THE TANK CAR, NOTED: A) ENTIRE TWO "SAFETY" MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT ASSEMBLIES, LOCATED AT THE MANWAY COVER HANDLE, AND THE AR HINGE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT ASSEMBLY, HAD BROKEN AWAY FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND WERE STILL ATTACHED TO THE COVER. THE TWO "SAFETY" BOLT SECUREMENT NUTS APPEARED NOT TOOL TIGHT-SECURED. THE AL HINGE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT NUT WAS TIGHT AGAINST COVER; B) TWO R-SIDE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS APPEARED TO HAVE NEVER BEEN SECURED PRIOR TO SHIPMENT, AS THEY WERE STILL ATTACHED TO THE MANWAY NOZZLE AS DESIGNED BY LAYING IN THE "UNSECURED" POSITION; C) ENTIRE TWO L-SIDE AND THE AL HINGE MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLT ASSEMBLIES (3 TOTAL) BROKE AWAY FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE/COVER AND WERE FOUND ON THE GROUND IN VARIOUS LOCATIONS. ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR REACT RESECURED THE MANWAY COVER UTILIZING C-CLAMPS AND THE TWO REMAINING MANWAY COVER SECUREMENT BOLTS; AND THE REMAINING CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED ON FRIDAY, 10/17/03, TO TANK CAR GCTX 413197, WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT. REACT IN PROCESS OF DESIGNING PROPER SECUREMENT OF THE MANWAY FOR TANK CAR TCDX 11010, TO HAVE IT SHIPPED BACK TO SHIPPER GENERAL CHEMICAL. column168: BNSF SWITCH FOREMAN BLEEDING OFF AIR ON AN INBOUND TRAIN, REPORTED LLCX 23216 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR. BNSF RESPONDERS PLACED A WADING POOL UNDER TANK CAR TO CATCH LEAKING PRODUCT. RESPONDERS FOUND PRODUCT STREAM COMING FROM A WELDED FLANGE PLATE LOCATED WHERE A BOTTOM OUTLET WOULD NORMALLY RESIDE. FLANGE PLATE APPEARED TO HAVE A 3/8-INCH PRE-DRILLED HOLE IN THE PLATE CENTER WHERE PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING, AS WELL AS, PRODUCT DRIPS ALONG THE WELD ON THE OUTSIDE CIRCUMFERENCE OF THE FLANGE PLATE. RESPONDERS PLUGGED HOLE WITH A WOODEN PEG/PLUG DRIVEN INTO THE HOLE & "PLUG-N-DIKE" USED TO SEAL THE FLANGE PLATE ALONG THE WELDED CIRCUMFERENCE. PRODUCT RELEASE WAS FULLY STOPPED AT 1545 HRS. CDT, 10/24. POSSIBLE LINER FAILURE WAS SUSPECTED & REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR BY 1545 HRS. CDT, 10/25. AFTERWARDS, A CLEAN VACUUM TRUCK WAS USED TO PURGE LLCX 23216 OF ANY REMAINING PRODUCT. SPILLED PRODUCT THAT IMPACTED GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED & EXCAVATED. BNSF CONTRACTOR ALSO PERFORMED AIR MONITORING DURING THIS EVENT. THE BNSF EMPLOYEE THAT DISCOVERED LEAK WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL COMPLAINING OF INHALATION EXPOSURE & ADMITTED FOR OVERNIGHT OBSERVATION. EMPLOYEE RELEASED FROM HOSPITAL & ISSUED PRESCRIPTION. EMPLOYEE LOST 19 DAYS OF WORK THROUGH 11/12/03.

THERE WERE 7 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CARS AMONG THE DERAILED CARS, INCLUDING; 3 RESIDUE TANK CARS THAT LAST CONTAINED SPENT SULFURIC ACID (GATX7448, GATX7445, GATX7498), 1 LOADED TANK CAR OF METHYL ETHYL KETONE (UTLX48187), 1 LOADED TANK CAR OF VINYL ACETATE (NLTX5010), AND 1 LOADED COVERED HOPPER OF AMMONIUM NITRATE (CSXT250414). THE UTLX48187, METHYL ETHYL KETONE, WAS PUNCTURED ON IMPACT AND CAUGHT FIRE. THE NLTX5010, VINYL ACETATE, WAS DERAILED NEAR THE UTLX48187 AND WAS EXPOSED TO A POOL FIRE OF THE METHYL ETHYL KETONE. PRESSURE BUILDUP IN THE NLTX5010 CAUSED THE TANK TO RUPTURE AND THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WAS CONSUMED IN THE FIRE. IN ADDITION, CSXT250414, AMMONIUM NITRATE, WAS TURNED OVER AND SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 2500 POUNDS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND. THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASE FROM ANY OF THE RESIDUE SPENT SULFURIC ACID CARS. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND DECIDED TO ALLOW THE TANK CAR TO CONTINUE TO BURN. THE AREA IS REMOTE AND THERE WERE NO EVACUATIONS OR MAJOR HIGHWAY CLOSURES. STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED. SHIPPERS WERE NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS TO CONDUCT THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP. AN INDUSTRIAL HYGIENE COMPANY RESPONDED AT THE REQUEST OF CSXT TO CONDUCT AIR MONITORING AROUND THE DERAILMENT SITE. column168: (A-C) AT APPROXIMATELY 1615HRS ON 10-25-2003, CSX TRANSPORTATION'S (CSXT) TRAIN, Q61824 WITH 87 LOADS AND 11 EMPTIES, DERAILED 25 RAIL CARS NEAR SHORTERS, AL, AT RAILROAD MILEPOST XXB 151.7. THERE WERE 7 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CARS AMONG THE DERAILED CARS, INCLUDING; 3 RESIDUE TANK CARS THAT LAST CONTAINED SPENT SULFURIC ACID (GATX7448, GATX7445, GATX7498), 1 LOADED TANK CAR OF METHYL ETHYL KETONE (UTLX48187), 1 LOADED TANK CAR OF VINYL ACETATE (NLTX5010), AND 1 LOADED COVERED HOPPER OF AMMONIUM NITRATE (CSXT250414). THE UTLX48187, METHYL ETHYL KETONE, WAS PUNCTURED ON IMPACT AND CAUGHT FIRE. THE NLTX5010, VINYL ACETATE, WAS DERAILED NEAR THE UTLX48187 AND WAS EXPOSED TO A POOL FIRE OF THE METHYL ETHYL KETONE. PRESSURE BUILDUP IN THE NLTX5010 CAUSED THE TANK TO RUPTURE AND THE CONTENTS OF THE CAR WAS CONSUMED IN THE FIRE. IN ADDITION, CSXT250414, AMMONIUM NITRATE, WAS TURNED OVER AND SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 2500 POUNDS OF PRODUCT ONTO THE GROUND. THERE WAS NO PRODUCT RELEASE FROM ANY OF THE RESIDUE SPENT SULFURIC ACID CARS. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AND DECIDED TO ALLOW THE TANK CAR TO CONTINUE TO BURN. THE AREA IS REMOTE AND THERE WERE NO EVACUATIONS OR MAJOR HIGHWAY CLOSURES. STATE AND FEDERAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED. SHIPPERS WERE NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTORS TO CONDUCT THE ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP. AN INDUSTRIAL HYGIENE COMPANY RESPONDED AT THE REQUEST OF CSXT TO CONDUCT AIR MONITORING AROUND THE DERAILMENT SITE. IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE MAJORITY OF THE METHYL ETHYL KETONE AND THE VINYL ACETATE WERE CONSUMED IN THE FIRE. ENVIRONMENTAL MONITORING OF THE SITE CONTINUES.

ON 10/21/03 AT APPROXIMATELY 16:30 A DRIVER FOR CTL DISTRIBUTION, INC WAS LOADED OVER THE LEGAL GROSS WEIGHT LIMIT. THE DRIVER FOR CTL DISTRIBUTION, INC RETURNED BACK TO THE LOADING STATION TO REMOVE ENOUGH PRODUCT IN ORDER TO MEET THE LEGAL WEIGHT REQUIREMENT. THE DRIVER FOR CTL DISTRIBUTION, INC. HOOKED UP TO THE UNLOADING LINE TO REMOVE THE PRODUCT FROM THE CARGO TANK. WHEN THE DRIVER CLOSED THE VALVES ON THE CARGO TANK AFTER REMOVING WHAT HE THOUGH WOULD BE ENOUGH PRODUCT HE USE AIR PRESSURE TO CLEAR THE PRODUCT FROM THE CUSTOMER UNLOADING LINE.  THE DRIVER AT THE TIME DID NOT REALIZE THAT ONE OF THE CUSTOMERS VALVES WAS STILL IN THE CLOSED POSITION.  AS THE DRIVER CLEARED THE UNLOADING LINE THE CUSTOMERS HOSE FAILED AND RUPTURED. A SPRAY OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE CUSTOMERS UNLOADING HOSE AND WHEN THE DRIVER TURNED HIS HEAD AWAY FROM THE PRODUCT SPRAY SOME OF THE PRODUCT WENT AROUND THE BACK OF THE DRIVERS HARD-HAT AND FACE-SHIELD. THE DRIVER RECEIVED BURNS TO HIS EARS AND CHEEK AREA ON HIS FACE.  THE DRIVER WAS WEARING ALL OF THE REQUIRED PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AT THE TIME THE INCIDENT OCCURRED. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY FLUSHED THE PRODUCT OFF THE AFFECTED AREAS UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER.  THE DRIVER WAS TREATED FOR HIS BURNS BY THE PLANT FIRST AID PROVIDER AND DIRECTED TO SEEK ADDITIONAL MEDICAL TREATMENT. CTL DISTRIBUTION TRANSPORTED THE DRIVER TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM FOR FURTHER EVALUATION. THE DRIVER WAS RELEASED THE SAME DAY AND WAS RELEASED BACK TO FULL DUTY.  THE DRIVER DID NOT MISS ANY TIME AWAY FROM WORK. THE DRIVER DID NOT RECEIVE ANY FURTHER MEDICAL TREATMENT AND HAS NOT HAD ANY ADDITIONAL COMPLICATION. THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND PLANT PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED PLANT PROCEDURES AND PROPER AUTHORIZATION FOR OPERATING CUSTOMER'S VALVES.

WHILE UNLOADING AT TERMINAL FACILITY, SUBJECT CONTAINER WAS STRUCK AND PUNCTURED BY FORKLIFT, CAUSING ACID TO SPILL ON TO TRAILER FLOOR AND GROUND (SOIL) SURFACES.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR (HMHTTC) WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO NEUTRALIZE SPILLED ACID WITH SODA ASH AND DECON OF TRAILER. IMPACTED SOILS WERE EXCAVATED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL AND REPLACED.  NO STORM DRAINS OR WATERWAYS WERE IMPACTED.

ON NOVEMBER 18, 2003, OLIN CORP ADVISED CSX TRANSPORTATION OF A CONDITION REPORTED TO THEM BY THEIR CUSTOMER, E I DUPONT AT AMPTHILL, VA.  OVER THE COURSE OF THE PAST YEAR AND ONE HALF, DUPONT HAS DISCOVERED SMALL AMOUNTS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE RESIDUE AROUND THE BASE OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) ON 39 TANK CARS AFTER THEY HAD BEEN UNLOADED AT THE AMPTHILL, VA FACILITY.  ALL OF THE CARS ARE EQUIPPED WITH MIDLAND EXTERNAL PRD AND THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE TO INDICATE THE RESIDUE PRESENT WAS THE RESULT OF A PRODUCT RELEASE DURING TRANSPORTATION.  OLIN INSPECTED AND TESTED SEVERAL OF THE PRD'S AND FOUND NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS OR DEFECTS WITH THEM.  OLIN REQUESTED CSXT'S ASSISTANCE TO REVIEW THE ROUTING AND HANDLING OF THEIR TANK CARS TRANSPORTED TO DUPONT'S AMPTHILL, VA PLANT.  THE ROUTING INDICATED THE CARS SHIPPED FROM OLIN'S NIAGARA FALLS, NY PLANT WERE SWITCHED AT CSXT'S RAIL YARDS IN NIAGARA FALLS, NY, SELKIRK, NY, RICHMOND, VA AND BELLWOOD, VA FOR DELIVERY TO DUPONT AT AMPTHILL.  THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE FROM CSXT, DUPONT, OR OLIN THAT ANY OF THE CARS IN QUESTION HAD EXPERIENCED ANY UNUSUAL HANDLING OR HARD COUPLING'S IN TRANSIT.  CSXT WITH OLIN'S COOPERATION HAS INITIATED A PLAN TO EQUIP SEVERAL TANK CARS WITH IMPACT RECORDERS THAT WILL MONITOR COUPLING IMPACTS TO DETERMINE IF CAR HANDLING COULD BE A CONTRIBUTING FACTOR IN A POSSIBLE PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THE PRD'S.  THE STUDY WILL BEGIN THE LATTER PART OF DECEMBER AND WILL CONTINUE INTO THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2004.  EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE THAT THE RESIDUE DISCOVERED AROUND THE PRD'S WAS DUE TO A PRODUCT RELEASE IN TRANSIT, CSXT IS SUBMITTING THIS REPORT IN ACCORDANCE WITH 171.16 OF THE US DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS REGULATIONS, 49 CFR.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER WAS MAKING A LEFT HAND TURN ONTO HWY. 67 NORTH AT EXIT 55.  THE ROAD WAS WET FROM RAIN.  HALFWAY THROUGH THE TURN, THE LOAD SHIFTED, AND THE TRUCK BEGAN TO SLIDE.  THERE WAS A STEEP DITCH ON THE RIGHT SIDE WHICH CAUSED THE TRUCK TO ROLLED OVER.  ACTION TAKEN AT THE TIME DISCOVERED: THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED US OF THE ACCIDENT.  I FIRST CALLED THE WHITE COUNTY SHERIFF FOR MORE INFORMATION.  THE SHERIFF PUT ME IN TOUCH WITH THE FIRE CHIEF ON THE SCENE.I ASKED THE CHIEF IF THERE WAS A FIRE AND IF THE TANK WAS LEAKING. HE SAID THERE WAS NO FIRE AT THIS TIME AND THE TANK DID NOT APPEAR TO BE LEAKING.  AFTER TALKING TO THE CHIEF, I DECIDED TO DISPATCH A CLEAN UP CREW TO BE ON SITE AND READY IF SPILL OCCURRED.  WHILE ENROUTE TO THE SCENE I ALSO DISPATCHED ANOTHER CARGO TANK FOR TRANSFERRING CARGO, AND TWO LARGE WRECKERS.  AFTER ARRIVING AT THE SCENE, I HAD THE CARGO TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TANK.  THEN THE WRECKER OPERATORS TURNED THE TRUCK AND TANK UPRIGHT.  LATER THE TRANSFERRED CARGO WAS MEASURED AND COMPARED TO THE LOADING TICKET.  IT WAS THEN DETERMINED THAT APPROXIMATELY 3000 GALLONS HAD BEEN SPILLED.  I NOTIFIED THE HAZMAT CLEANUP COMPANY AT THE SCENE.  THE HAZMAT CLEANUP CREW  REMAINED AT THE SCENE TO ENSURE A COMPLETE CLEANUP.  I WAS LATER NOTIFIED, BY THE CLEANUP COMPANY THAT THEY HAD RECOVERED APPROXIMATELY 3000 GALLONS OF SPILLED PRODUCT.  ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS:  WE CONDUCTED A COMPLETE AND DETAILED RECREATION OF EVENTS LEADING UP TO THE ACCIDENT WITH THE DRIVER.  WE ALSO DISCUSSED WAYS TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.  THE DRIVER WAS THEN ENROLLED IN A ROLLOVER PREVENTION COURSE.  WE ARE ENROLLING ALL OF OUR DRIVERS IN THIS COURSE TO BETTER EDUCATE THEM ON DRIVING SAFETY AND AWARENESS.

column168: BP DELIVERY DRIVER WAS MAKING ROUTINE DELIVERY AT ARCO FACILITY #5620 IN HESPERIA, CA.  HE FOLLOWED ROUTINE DELIVERY PROCEDURES BY FIRST INSURING TANK OUTAGE.  ONCE THIS WAS COMPLETE, HE COMMENCED HIS DELIVERY. APPARENTLY, HE MISCALCULATED HIS OUTAGE, BECAUSE AS HE WAS FILLING 1 OF 2 TANKS, THE TANK HE WAS UNLOADING INTO FILLED UP PUSHING PRODUCT THRU THE UNDERGROUND SIPHON PIPE TO THE ATTACHED TANK CAUSING THAT TANK TO OVERFILL INTO THE FILL BOX AND ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY HALTED THE UNLOADING BY SHUTTING DISCHARGE VALVE.  HE THEN BEGAN TO CLEAN UP SPILL WITH SPILL PADS THAT ARE CARRIED ON ALL BP DELIVERY TRUCKS.  DRIVER CLEANED UP SPILL AND NO OTHER SERVICES WERE REQUIRED.  THE SPILL WAS ESTIMATED AT TWO GALLONS.  THE INCIDENT WAS REVIEWED WITH THE BP DRIVER IN QUESTION AND HE WAS COUNSELED ON CORRECT DELIVERY PROCEDURES AND SPILL PREVENTION.

ON 10/08/03 AT 0352 A SHIPMENT WITH ODOR OF FINGERNAIL POLISH WAS REPORTED IN BUILDING 208 (LINE 3,7P AREA) OF OUR HAZMAT SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OH,45177. PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS THOMAS CASPER AND TERRY RUGGERIE DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH NO VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THEY REMOVED THIS BOX FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. UPON INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE BOX TO CONTAIN TWO SMALLER FIBERBOARD BOXES. ONE OF THESE SMALLER FIBERBOARD BOXES CONTAINED TWO PLASTIC ZIP-LOCK BAGS. EACH OF THESE BAGS CONTAINED 6 X 10 ML GLASS BOTTLES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES OF "NATURE" FINGERNAIL POLISH. THE CLOSURES ON THESE BOTTLES WERE NOT SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. ONE OF THESE BOTTLES WAS BROKEN ALLOWING IT TO LEAK ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS OF 10 ML. THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AND HAD THE PROPER SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOXES, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM. THIS SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION. THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR. SHE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND RETURNED TO HER WORK AREA. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED. NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED. CLEAR OF SCENE: 0413 THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT.

ON 10/04/2003 AT 0005 A LEAKING SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED AT DOOR "A-9" OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS KEVIN GAREN AND BILLI MARSH DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND SIX FIBERBOARD BOXES, ONE WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THE BOXES FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THE LEAKING BOX (MARKED 4 OF 6) TO CONTAIN THE FOLLOWING: 1 X12 OZ OF "SANDABLE PRIMER", 1 X6 OZ OF "ARRID EXTRA DRY", 1 X 2 OZ OF "FRIZZ-EASE" (ALL IN METAL AEROSOL CANS MARKED "CONTENTS UNDER PRESSURE"), 1 X 1 OZ GLASS BOTTLE WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE OF "TRUCK COLOR TOUCH UP", 1 X 1 LB METAL TUBE WITH A SCREW TYPE CLOSURE OF "DYNATRON GLAZING AND SPOT PUTTY" (BOTH MARKED "EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE"), 1 X 2.75 OZ AND 1 X .75 OZ PLASTIC TUBES WITH SCREW TYPE CLOSURES OF " CREAM HARDENER" (BOTH HAD FLAMMABLE SYMBOLS).  NONE OF THE CLOSURES ON THESE RECEPTACLES WERE SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURES ON THE "DYNATRON GLAZING AND SPOT PUTTY" AND THE .75 OZ TUBE OF "CREAM HARDENER" CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THEM TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 3 OZ EACH OF THEIR CONTENTS.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE BOXES, BOX NUMBER 6 OF 6  WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN 2 X 200 ML GLASS BOTTLES WITH PUMP SPRAY TYPE CLOSURES OF "GIVENCHY" COLOGNE.  THE LABELS ON THESE BOTTLES STATED "FLAMMABLE".  THESE BOTTLES DID NOT LEAK.  THESE TWO, AS WELL AS THE REMAING FOUR BOXES ALSO CONTAINED MISCELLANEOUS NON REGULATED PERSONAL ITEMS.  THE OTHER FOUR BOXES DID NOT CONTAIN ANY REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THEY REPLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOXES, SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENTS IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED THEM INTO RECOVERY DRUMS.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION. NONE OF THE CLOSURES ON THESE RECEPTACLES WERE SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS.  THE CLOSURES ON THE "DYNATRON GLAZING AND SPOT PUTTY" AND THE .75 OZ TUBE OF "CREAM HARDENER" CAME LOOSE ALLOWING THEM TO LEAK APPROXIMATELY 3 OZ EACH OF THEIR CONTENTS. THE OTHER FOUR BOXES DID NOT CONTAIN ANY REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. AT APPROXIMATELY 5:10 PM ON WEDNESDAY OCTOBER 8, 2003 I RECEIVED A CALL FROM HERMAN SCHOPPER, A DRIVER EMPLOYED BY N&M TRANSFER.  HERMAN INFORMED ME THAT HIM AND ANOTHER N&M TRANSFER DRIVER (JAMES PALMBACH) JUST BECAME AWARE OF A SPILL OF WHAT THEY THOUGHT WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL COMING OUT OF THE BACK OF JIM'S TRAILER.  HERMAN AND JIM WERE BOTH ON THE PROPERTY OF FIRE PLACE PRODUCTS, 515 BUSSE RD., ELK GROVE VILLAGE, IL. I IMMEDIATELY ADVISED HERMAN TO CALL 911.  OVER THE NEXT HOUR I CONTINUED TO DISCUSS THE SPILL WITH HERMAN AND JIM.  AS I QUESTIONED THE CHAIN OF EVENTS HERMAN STATED THAT HE HAD ALREADY PULLED HIS TRACTOR-TRAILER INTO THE DOCK AT FIREPLACE PRODUCTS.  JIM HAD ARRIVED AT FIRE PLACE PRODUCTS ABOUT 4:15 PM. NO DOCK OPEN SO HE SAT OUTSIDE IN THE LOT FOR ABOUT 15 MINUTES UNTIL 4:30 PM.  AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 A DOCK DOOR OPENED AND JIM BEGAN BACKING HIS TRAILER AGAINST THE A DOCK DOOR THAT WAS TWO DOORS TO THE RIGHT OF HERMAN'S TRAILER.  APPARENTLY HERMAN SAID HE HEARD A SCRAPING NOISE AS JIM WAS BACKING HIS TRAILER IN.  HE WAS CURIOUS SO WHEN HE WALKED TO THE DOCK DOOR JIM JUST PULLED IN TO, HE NOTICED THAT AN IGLOO COOLER WAS STUCK BETWEEN THE DOCK WALL AND THE TRAILER'S ICC BAR.  HERMAN THAN ATTEMPTED TO OPEN THE DOOR OF THE TRAILER AND HE ADVISED ME THEN THAT AT THE TIME A WAVE OF LIQUID BEGAN COMING OUT THE BACK DOOR ON TO THE DOCK PLATE AND GROUND SURFACE.  HERMAN IMMEDIATELY ADVISED JIM WHAT WAS HAPPENING.  JIM WENT BACK IN TO HIS TRUCK AND MOVED THE VEHICLE OUT ABOUT 20 FEET FROM THE DOCK. IN TO THE LOT.  (APPARENTLY THERE WAS STORM SEWER LOCATED ON THE GROUND AT THAT SPOT SO HE AGAIN MOVED THE TRAILER ABOUT 100 FEET TO ANOTHER LOT AT 501 BUSSE RD).  HE THEN NOTICED ANOTHER STORM SEWER IN THAT AREA, SO HE DECIDED TO MOVE THE TRAILER ANOTHER 700-800 FEET. (SEE PHOTO OF THE FINAL RESTING SPOT OF TRAILER IN THE PRIVATE PARKING LOT AREA).  LATER IT WAS REPORTED THAT ALL THREE AREAS WHERE JIM PARKED THE VEHICLE HAD SOME TYPE OF STORM SEWER.  AS FAR AS EMERGENCY PERSONNEL THE ELK GROVE VILLAGE POLICE WERE THE FIRST TO RESPOND TO THE SCENE.  THEY ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 5:20 PM.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED ANOTHER 5-10 MINUTES LATER.  OUR RECORDS INDICATED THAT A CITY-COUNTY HAZ/MAT TEAM WAS ON THE SCENE BY 5:28 PM. THERE WERE ALSO PERSONNEL FROM THE METROPOLITAN WATER REMEDIATION DEPARTMENT ON THE SCENE.  THE CAUSE OF THE SPILL (SEE PHOTOS OF RUPTURE AREA ON THE IBC'S).  AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT IT IS OFFICIALLY UNDETERMINED.  HOWEVER AFTER THE SPILL CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED AND ALL VEHICLES WERE RELEASED OUR DRIVERS INFORMED US THAT TWO OF THE 13 IBC'S WERE DRAINED BY THE REMEDIATION COMPANY HIRED BY OUR INSURANCE CARRIER. (SET ENVIRONMENTAL INC., 450 SUMAC RD. WHEELING, IL.,60090.)  ONE IBC WAS CLEARLY RUPTURED WITH AN ESTIMATED 6-8" CRACK IN THE TOP RIGHT SIDE.  I WAS ADVISED THAT THIS CRACK OPENED UP AT THE SPILL SITE WHEN SET ATTEMPTED TO DRAIN THIS TANK.  THE SECOND IBC ALSO SPILLED SOME MATERIAL, IT WAS ALSO DRAINED BECAU

I RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE GORDON COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT AT 07:15 STATING THAT ONE OF OUR TRUCKS HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED AT 06:56.  I ARRIVED AROUND 8:40 AND FOUND THAT OUR TRUCK HAD BEEN INVOLVED IN AN ACCIDENT WITH A COVENANT TRANSPORT TRUCK. OUR DRIVER (SHANNON DUNN) STATED THAT THE COVENANT DRIVER WAS TRAVELING AT A SLOWER PACE AND HE DID NOT SEE ANY LIGHTS ON THE TRAILER OF THE COVENANT UNIT UNTIL HE WAS RIGHT ON IT.  HE CHECKED THE LEFT LANE APPLYING BRAKES AT THE SAME TIME AND THEN SWERVED TO THE LEFT. HE CAUGHT THE LEFT REAR OF THE COVENANT TRAILER WITH THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE OF HIS TRUCK.  THE MOMENTUM WAS CARRYING HIM LEFT AND THEN THE RIGHT FRONT TIRE OF HIS TRUCK THEN CAUGHT THE REAR OF THE COVENANT TRAILER CAUSING HIM TO COME BACK OVER IN FRONT OF THE COVENANT TRUCK.  THEY DID NOT HIT EACH OTHER AS HE CAME BACK OVER IN FRONT OF THE COVENANT TRUCK.  SHANNON'S TRUCK HIT THE GUARDRAIL AND THEN CAME TO A STOP.  CONDITIONS AT THE TIME OF ACCIDENT WERE DARK, BUT NOT RAINING OR INCLEMENT WEATHER.  THE DRIVER OF THE CONVENANT TRUCK STATED THAT HE WAS HAVING MECHANICAL TROUBLE, TRAVELING AT 40-45 MPH, AND HAD HIS EMERGENCY FLASHERS ON.  HE ALSO STATED THAT HE WAS AS FAR OVER IN THE EMERGENCY LANE BUT DUE TO THE GUARDRAIL BEING AS CLOSE AS IT WAS, HE WAS NOT ENTIRELY OUT OF THE ROAD.  UPON MY ARRIVAL, THE FLASHERS ON THE COVENANT POWER UNIT WERE WORKING, BUT NO SIGNS OF ANY LIGHTS WORKING ON THE TRAILER.  MARION ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL AND UNIVAR PERSONNEL TRANSFERRED THE GOOD MATERIAL OVER TO ANOTHER UNIVAR UNIT FOR TRANSPORTATION BACK TO THE BRANCH. column168: FREIGHT WAS ON A CITY P AND D ROUTE WHEN LEAK WAS DETECTED.  DRIVER JIM DANIEL, INFORMED FOS BRACEY HOWELL AT 1250 ABOUT THE SPILL.  THERE WAS A MINOR AMOUNT LEAKING FROM THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  HOWELL CONTACTED MIKE SORENSON AT 1250 AND THEN RECEIVED A RETURN CALL FROM JEFF TURNER WHO WAS TRAVELING.  HOWELL FOLLOWED SORENSON'S INSTRUCTIONS WHICH FOLLOWS.  HOWELL CONTACTED CONAGRA TO SEE IF THEY HAD A CHEMICAL SPILL TEAM TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  THIS CAME VOID.  AT 1320, STEVE AT JOHNSON DIVERSITY CONTACTED HOWELL ABOUT THE SPILL WITH NO AVAILABLE HELP.  HOWELL THEN CONTACTED CHEMTREC AND SPOKE WITH KIP.  KIP ASSIGNED A CHEMTREC #11032003053.  KIP INFORMED HOWELL TO CONTACT THE FIRE DEPT.  AFTER TRANSFERRING LINE SEVERAL TIMES, HOWELL CONTACTED KATIE AT OREGON EMERGENCY RESPONSE AT 1410.  AT THIS TIME, THE DRIVER WAS NOT RELEASED TO CONTINUE THE ROUTE PER FOS. KATIE ASSIGNED #032471 TO THE SPILL.  KIMBERLY FROM THE DEQ CALLED AT 1440 TO GET MORE INFORMATION.  HOWELL STAYED IN CONTACT WITH SHIPPER UNIVAR'S ROBERT MATTSON DURING THE ENTIRE SPILL.  PAT HART FROM THE HERMISTON FIRE DEPT CALLED TO RESPOND.  AFTER ALL IS SAID AND DONE, HART RELEASED DRIVER TO DELIVER FREIGHT.  HART TOOK PICTURES OF FREIGHT AND WILL FORWARD TO HOWELL.  HART AND CREW CLAIMED THAT THE LEAK WAS FROM THE BUNG OF THE TOTE. COMPLETE SHIPPER ERROR.

column168: ON OCTOBER 31, 2003 PASSENGER CRISTINA SILVERIO WAS TRAVELING BACK TO JFK FROM SANTIAGO, DOMINICAN REPUBLIC ON FLIGHT 2054, WHICH DEPARTED SANTIAGO AT 419 PM.  ABOUT 1 AND A HALF-HOURS INTO THE FLIGHT, THE FLIGHT ATTENDANTS NOTICED THE SMELL OF FUMES IN THE CABIN.  IN ATTEMPTING TO DETERMINE WHERE THE FUMES WERE COMING FROM, THE FLIGHT ATTENDANTS NOTICED THAT THE FUMES WERE VERY HIGH IN THE ROW CRISTINA SILVERIO WAS SEATED.  WHEN PASSENGERS IN THE ROW WERE QUESTIONED CRISTINA SAID SHE WAS TRAVELING WITH A REMEDY WHICH INCLUDED SOME TYPE OF GAS.  THE SUBSTANCE, WHICH CONTAINED KEROSENE, WAS CARRIED IN A PINT OF WHISKEY BOTTLE.  CRISTINA SAID THE LIQUID WAS USED FOR MEDICINAL PURPOSES AND ALSO SAID THAT SHE KNEW ABOUT THE DANGEROUS GOOD BUT HAD FORGOTTEN ABOUT IT.  DURING THE FLIGHT SOME OF THE LIQUID SPILLED IN THE OVERHEAD BIN AND THAT WAS HOW THE FUMES WERE RELEASED INTO THE CABIN. UPON THE FLIGHT'S ARRIVAL AT JFK AIRCRAFT MECHANIC ROLAND RUPPERT CLEANED THE OVERHEAD BIN.  IN ADDITION CRISTINA WAS TOLD THAT IN THE FUTURE SHE MUST DECLARE ANY DANGEROUS GOOD PRIOR TO BOARDING AN AIRCRAFT.  SHE WAS INFORMED THAT DANGEROUS GOOD SHOULD BE DECLARED AT THE TICKET COUNTER WHEN SHE CHECKS IN.  SHE WAS ALSO INFORMED THAT DANGEROUS GOODS WERE NOT TO BE TRANSPORT ON AMERICAN AIRLINES.  WE ALSO INFORMED HER THAT WE WOULD FOLLOW UP WITH THE DEPT OF TRANSPORTATION TO LET THEM KNOW THAT SHE WAS TRANSPORTING A HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOOD.  CRISTINA SAID SHE UNDERSTOOD AND WOULD DECLARE AND NOT TRANSPORT ANY DANGEROUS GOODS ON AMERICAN AGAIN.

column168: UPRR'S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATIONS CENTER NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, OF A REPORT OF A TANK CAR LEAKING IN KANSAS CITY, KS.  LES MAKOVEC, SMTO, HAD REPORTED UTLX 200526, A LOAD OF HYDROGEN PEROXIDE, TO BE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  MR. SEKAVEC, WAS IN BEATRICE, NE, AND CONTACTED CHRIS WILLIAMS, MYO, WHO ADVISED THE CAR ONLY APPEARED TO BE LEAKING WHEN IT WAS MOVED.  MR. SEKAVEC CONTACTED TED SATTUR WITH DEGUSSA CORPORATION (SHIPPER) TO ADVISE HIM OF THE PROBLEM AND DETERMINE IF DEGUSSA HAD A LOCAL RESPONDER TO ASSESS THE PROBLEM AND MAKE REPAIRS IF POSSIBLE.  MR. SEKAVEC ALSO CONTACTED DAVE TYLER AT ARM DAT (CONSIGNEE) FOR ASSISTANCE AS WELL.  MR. TYLER RESPONDED AND DETERMINED THE FRANGIBLE DISK HAD RUPTURED IN THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE, PROBABLY DUE TO A HYDRAULIC SURGE FROM A HARD COUPLING.  MR. TYLER REPLACED THE RUPTURED DISK WITH A NEW DISK THAT WAS STORED ON THE CAR.  HE ALSO WASHED THE CAR AND SURROUNDING AREA DOWN TO PREVENT ANY REACTION BETWEEN THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND ANY ORGANIC MATERIAL THAT MAY HAVE BEEN CONTACTED.  NO ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT IS EXPECTED FROM THIS INCIDENT AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

AT APPROXIMATELY 2200HRS ON 10-19-03, CTS MGR LERCH RESPONDED TO A LEAKING TANK CAR LOCATED IN THE STRANG YARD TRACK 117 IN LA PORTE, TX. ON ARRIVAL MGR LERCH NOTED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE AREA OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE NOZZLE AT THE RATE OF LESS THAN ONE GALLON PER HOUR.  HE PLACED A CONTAINMENT POOL BELOW THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  MGR LERCH HAD THE SHIPPER, EASTMAN CHEMICAL CONTACTED VIA CHEM-TREC AND SPOKE TO DARYL GREER, FIRE CAPTAIN AND STEVE JONES, TEAM MGR BULK LOADING, REQUESTING AN MSDS. MGR LERCH INFORMED MR JONES THE TANK SHELL HAD FAILED IN THE AREA WHERE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE NOZZLE IS ATTACHED TO THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK CAR. ARRANGEMENTS WERE THEN MADE BY MR JONES TO HAVE HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES OFF LOAD THE CAR INTO TANK TRUCKS AND REMEDIATE THE AFFECTED AREA WITH THE APPLICATION OF SODA ASH.  THE CONTAINMENT POOL WAS SECURED TO THE CAR, AND THE CAR WAS THEN MOVED TO TRACK 214 FOR OFF LOADING.  TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS COMPLETED AT APPROXIMATELY 1030HRS WITH THE USE OF FOUR TANK TRUCKS.  PRODUCT WAS MOVED TO BEE LINE TERMINAL FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION. AT APPROXIMATELY 1030HRS WITH THE USE OF FOUR TANK TRUCKS.  PRODUCT WAS MOVED TO BEE LINE TERMINAL FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1230HRS HULCHER PERSONNEL CLEARED THE SCENE.  AFTER COMPLETION OF THE TRANSFER, A CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE CAR WAS CONDUCTED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE FAILURE WAS UNDERNEATH THE REINFORCEMENT PAD WHERE THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE NOZZLE IS ATTACHED TO THE CAR.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM A THREADED 1/4 INCH WEEP HOLE WITHIN THE REINFORCEMENT PAD.  AFTER IDENTIFYING THE SOURCE OF THE RELEASE, MGR LERCH ADVISED JULIE BROWN, LOGISTICS COMPLIANCE MGR FOR EASTMAN CHEMICAL.  MS. BROWN FILED FOR A MOVEMENT AUTHORITY WITH THE FRA TO MOVE THE CAR TO HOME SHOP FOR REPAIRS WITH A 1/4 PLUG SECURED INTO THE THREADED WEEP HOLE.  AFTER RECEIVING THE MOVEMENT AUTHORITY ON 10-23-03, MGR LERCH & HULCHER ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL SCREWED TRANSPORTATION TO THE DESIGNATED CAR REPAIR FACILITY IN HEARNE, TX. WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

column168: STEVE HAMPTON, MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS - PHOENIX, REQUESTED TANKCAR ASTX 3026 TO BE INSPECTED.  MR. HAMPTON REPORTED THERE WAS EVIDENCE THAT THE TANKCAR HAD LEAKED AT SOME TIME, THE CAR WAS NOT CURRENTLY LEAKING AND JUST HAD STAINS ON ITS SIDE.  THE CAR WAS STATIONARY AND IN MESA IN YARD 6 TRACK 111, TWO CARS FROM THE WEST SIDE.  DENNIS JOHNSON, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY MANAGER, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MANAGER JOHNSON REPORTED APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE BODY OF THE TANKCAR AS A RESULT OF THREE LOOSE SECURING BOLTS ON THE FILL HOLE LID. MR. JOHNSON STATED THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO DECONTAMINATE THE TANKCAR.  RMCC MADE NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC, MESA FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND APPROPRIATE STATE AGENCIES.  ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE, CONTRACTOR, COMPLETED DECONTAMINATION OF THE RAILCAR AT 6:18 P.M.

JIM SWEENEY, CHIEF CLERK, REPORTED AN UNKNOWN SUBSTANCE WAS RELEASED FROM THE FRONT LEFT PORTION OF CONTAINER CSXU 685168, A LOAD OF MIXED HAZMAT, WHICH WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING TRANSPORTED TO THE HAZMAT AREA OF THE CITY OF INDUSTRY YARD.  MR. SWEENEY STATED APPROXIMATELY  ONE CUP OF THE CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS RELEASED AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND STATED A CONTRACTOR WOULD BE DISPATCHED TO THE AREA.  THE CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THAT 12 DRUMS HAD LOOSE BUNGS AND ONE TOTE HAD A LOOSE FILL HOLE.  THE LOOSE BUNGS AND FILL HOLE WERE TIGHTENED.  THE CONTRACTOR FURTHER REPORTED TWO OUNCES OF AN UNKNOWN ACIDIC INORGANIC CORROSIVE LIQUID WAS RELEASED ON THE GROUND AT THE YARD.  RMCC NOTIFIED STATE, COUNTY, AND FEDERAL AGENCIES, AS WELL AS CHEMTREC.

column168: ON TUESDAY, OCTOBER 21, 2003 AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 AM, THE REAR TIRES OF THIS BAR-BEL TRAILER (CARGO TANK) CAUGHT FIRE DUE TO BRAKE DRUM MALFUNCTION.  THE FIRE/INCIDENT OCCURRED ON I-65 S EN ROUTE FROM NUCOR STEEL, DECATUR IN TRINITY, AL TO BAILEY-PVS OXIDES, LLC IN FAIRFIELD, AL. ACCORDING TO ALAN KNIPHFER OF THE JEFFERSON COUNTY EMA, APPROXIMATELY 100 GAL OF THE LADING, FERROUS CHLORIDE, WAS RELEASED TO THE GROUND AS A RESULT OF THE OVER-PRESSURIZATION OF THE LIQUID CAUSED BY THE BOILING CAUSED BY THE FIRE.  TRAFFIC WAS STOPPED TEMPORARILY TO ALLOW RESPONSE CREWS TO ATTEND TO THE INCIDENT.  ALL CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED 10/22.
